  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are a number of international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. These efforts are primarily focused on:\n\n*   **Criminalizing money laundering:** Making it illegal to conceal or disguise the proceeds of criminal activities.\n*   **Establishing regulatory frameworks:** Requiring financial institutions and other businesses to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n*   **Promoting international cooperation:** Encouraging countries to share information and assist each other in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.\n\nSome key international legal instruments and initiatives include:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This treaty was one of the first international efforts to address money laundering, specifically in the context of drug trafficking.\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expanded the scope of international cooperation against money laundering to cover a broader range of criminal activities.\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n*   **The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):** This convention focuses on asset recovery and international cooperation in confiscating the proceeds of crime.\n\nThese laws and agreements provide a framework for countries to develop their own domestic anti-money laundering laws and regulations. They also encourage international cooperation in combating this global problem.",
